Define Database

A database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed so it can be easily accessed, updated, and analyzed.

In simple terms, a database is like a digital filing system where information is stored in a structured way.

Why Do We Need a Database?

Before databases, data was stored in files (paper or basic computer files). This caused problems like:

Data duplication

Data inconsistency

Difficult searching

Poor security

Databases solve these problems by organizing and controlling data efficiently.

Example of a Database

Imagine a school database:

Student ID	  Name	   Class	  Marks
101	           Ali	   10	      85
102	           Sara	   10	      90

Instead of storing this in random files, a database keeps it structured so you can:

Add new students
Update marks
Search by name
Delete records

Types of Databases
1 Relational Database

Stores data in tables (rows and columns)
Uses SQL (Structured Query Language)
Most common type

Examples:
MySQL
Oracle Database
Microsoft SQL Server

2 NoSQL Database

Stores data in flexible formats (JSON, key-value, documents)
Used for big data and real-time applications
Examples:
MongoDB
Cassandra

Main Components of a Database

Tables – Store data
Rows (Records) – Individual entries
Columns (Fields) – Data attributes
Primary Key – Unique identifier
Queries – Commands to retrieve data

Simple Definition (Exam-Friendly)

A database is a structured collection of related data stored electronically and managed by a DBMS for easy access, modification, and control.

