RDBMS (Relational Database Management System)

An RDBMS is a type of DBMS that stores data in the form of tables (rows and columns) and manages relationships between those tables.

In simple words:

RDBMS is a system that stores related data in tables and connects them using keys.

Why is it called “Relational”?

Because it is based on the Relational Model introduced by E. F. Codd, where data in different tables is related using:

Primary Key (unique identifier)

Foreign Key (connects one table to another)

🔹 Example
Table 1: Students
Student_ID (PK)	Name	Class
101	            Ali	  10
102	            Sara	10

Table 2: Marks
Student_ID (FK)	Subject	Marks
101	            Math	85
102	            Math	90

Here:

Student_ID in Students table is Primary Key

Student_ID in Marks table is Foreign Key

Both tables are related

Features of RDBMS

✔ Data stored in tables
✔ Relationships between tables
✔ Uses SQL language
✔ Reduces data duplication
✔ Ensures data integrity
✔ Supports multi-user access

Examples of RDBMS Software

MySQL
Oracle Database
Microsoft SQL Server
PostgreSQL

Advantages of RDBMS

Easy to use
High security
Data consistency
Backup and recovery support

