Explain Normalization in RDBMS

Normalization in RDBMS

Normalization is the process of organizing data in a database to reduce redundancy (duplicate data) and improve data integrity.

In simple words:

Normalization means arranging data properly into tables so that repetition is minimized and relationships are maintained correctly.

Normalization is mainly used in RDBMS systems like:

MySQL
Oracle Database
Microsoft SQL Server

Why Do We Need Normalization?

Without normalization:
Data is repeated many times
Storage is wasted
Updating data becomes difficult
Inconsistency problems occur
Normalization solves these problems.

Types of Normal Forms

Normalization is done in steps called Normal Forms (NF).

First Normal Form (1NF)

Rules:

Table must have no repeating groups

Each column contains atomic (single) values

Each record is unique

❌ Not in 1NF:

Student	Subjects
Ali	    Math, English

✅ In 1NF:

Student	Subject
Ali	  Math
Ali	  English

Second Normal Form (2NF)

Rules:

Must be in 1NF
No partial dependency
All non-key attributes must depend on the entire primary key
This usually applies when we have composite keys.

Third Normal Form (3NF)

Rules:

Must be in 2NF
No transitive dependency
Non-key attributes should depend only on the primary key

Example:
If a table stores:

| Student_ID | Student_Name | Class | Class_Teacher |

If Class_Teacher depends on Class (not directly on Student_ID),
then we separate into two tables:

Students Table
Classes Table

Boyce-Codd Normal Form (BCNF) - Not required for now

Advanced version of 3NF

Every determinant must be a candidate key

Used in complex database structures.

Advantages of Normalization

✔ Reduces data redundancy
✔ Improves data consistency
✔ Saves storage space
✔ Makes updates easier
✔ Improves database structure

In Short:
Normalization is the process of organizing data in an RDBMS into multiple related tables to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity.

