Explain Database Design in RDBMS

Database Design in RDBMS

Database Design in an RDBMS is the process of planning and structuring a database so that data is stored efficiently, accurately, and securely.

In simple words:

Database design means deciding what data to store, how to store it in tables, and how tables will relate to each other.

It is done in systems like:

MySQL
Oracle Database
Microsoft SQL Server
PostgreSQL

Steps in Database Design
1 Requirement Analysis

Understand what information is needed.
Identify users and their needs.
Example: For a school system → Students, Teachers, Classes, Marks.

Conceptual Design (ER Model)

2 Create an Entity-Relationship (ER) Diagram

Identify:
Entities (Student, Course)
Attributes (Name, ID, Age)

Relationships (Student enrolls in Course)

This step is logical planning, not actual tables.

3 Logical Design

Convert ER diagram into tables

Define:
Primary Keys
Foreign Keys
Relationships
Apply Normalization (1NF, 2NF, 3NF)
Example:

Students Table
Student_ID (Primary Key)
Name
Class

Marks Table
Student_ID (Foreign Key)
Subject
Marks

4 Physical Design

Decide how data will be stored physically.

Define:
Indexes
Storage type
Performance optimization

Important Concepts in Database Design
✔ Primary Key
Unique identifier for each record.

✔ Foreign Key
Connects two tables.

✔ Normalization
Removes redundancy.

✔ Constraints
Rules applied to data (NOT NULL, UNIQUE, etc.)

✔ Indexes
Improve search performance.

Goals of Good Database Design

✔ Minimize data redundancy
✔ Ensure data integrity
✔ Improve performance
✔ Easy maintenance
✔ Security control

